         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... these (go) towards him ... As disciples to a teacher, these now</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (not having been ...) like ... they go readily with the wish to see Metrak.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... to the noble Metrak, who (has come) here from the Dakṣiṇāpatha passing through many lands</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Mount Pāṣāṇaka, the jewel of the land of Magadha, where this one, (the teacher) of the three worlds,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4 #a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… the Mount Pāṣāṇaka, the jewel of the land of Magadha, where this one, (the teacher) of the three worlds, … the Buddha, the teacher, will keep waiting for the noble Maitreya</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>625</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Buddha-god the teacher will keep waiting for the noble Metrak’s going away from the house. God Brahmā says:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... innumerable Kinnaras and Gandharvas around the Buddha-god the teacher in order to hear the Law.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Let us do it in this way! And now, by seeing son and father, both kings of Buddha rank, with both (our) eyes</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Bodhisattva Metrak, with the fifteen brahmin youths beginning with Ajita, and 400,000 adherents of the Vinaya,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... with the wish to go away from the house to (the Buddha-god) the teacher, going through the lands of Magadha, on the Mount Pāṣāṇaka</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the kings of the Asuras, beginning with Rāhu-Svarbhānu and Vemacitra, the (kings) of the Nāgas starting with Piṅgala and Elapatra,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the innumerable and countless kings of the Kinnaras and Gandharvas (saw) the venerable Metrak (with his) multi-colored</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having put on the <hi>yajñopavīta</hi> rosary, wrapped in a supple, gold-colored cloak, with sandals decorated with pearls</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... adorned, like the God Brahmā (seen) in his own face, having come to Mount Pāṣāṇaka,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... that divine crowd rose everywhere from their seats. || In the Śmāśānaśräṅkār [tune] ||</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... astonished, they addressed the venerable Metrak: Good</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (the teacher) of matchless Buddha rank. 1 For what reason</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">The commentary is adapted from <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>112</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="parallels">MaitrHami 2, 10-11</note><note type="remarks">This fragment contains part of the second act of the Maitreyasamitināṭaka; an Uy. parallel is MaitrHami II, 10a6-11a10. See also <bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault1999"/><citedRange>195-6</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">The translation and the following commentary are adapted from <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>112</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 a7ff., and the last line of this leaf corresponds roughly to MaitrHami 2, 11 a7ff. (for the Uy. references, cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>18</citedRange></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment">The <hi>ṣṣ</hi> at the beginning of this line is certainly the ending of a past participle.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 a16; God Brahmā is speaking.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 a27ff.</note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 b3; God Indra is speaking.</note><note corresp="#a8" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 b8ff.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 10 b17ff.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment"><hi>ājāl</hi>: The reading is certain; because of the /j/ consonant, the word must be a borrowing, possibly from a Prakritic form corresponding to Skt. <hi>akṣāvali-</hi> ‘rosary’, cf. Skt. <hi>akṣa-valaya-</hi>, <hi>akṣa-mālā</hi>, etc.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment">Cf. MaitrHami 2, 11 a1-3ff. <hi>śmāśānaśräṅkāraṃ</hi>: two stanzas of presumably 4 x 18 (7/7/4) syllables; this metrical passage ends in the following leaf, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-yqii10"/>: a2, where the number ‘1’ should be a mistake for ‘2’.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment"><hi>pkāk</hi>: pace <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1999b"/><citedRange>281</citedRange></bibl>, there is no trace of <distinct type="ms_text">_u</distinct>, i.e. <distinct type="ms_text">p_ukāk</distinct>. Compare e.g. the akṣara <hi>ṣkā</hi> in the same line.</note></p>
